[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The **`reduce()`** method of `Array` instances executes a user-supplied "reducer" callback function on each element of the array, in order, passing in the return value from the calculation on the preceding element.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The final result of running the reducer across all elements of the array is a single value.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The first time that the callback is run there is no "return value of the previous calculation".
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] If supplied, an initial value may be used in its place.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Otherwise the array element at index 0 is used as the initial value and iteration starts from the next element (index 1 instead of index 0).
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] A function to execute for each element in the array.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Its return value becomes the value of the `accumulator` parameter on the next invocation of `callbackFn`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] For the last invocation, the return value becomes the return value of `reduce()`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The value resulting from the previous call to `callbackFn`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] On the first call, its value is `initialValue` if the latter is specified; otherwise its value is `array[0]`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] On the first call, its value is `array[0]` if `initialValue` is specified; otherwise its value is `array[1]`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The index position of `currentValue` in the array.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] On the first call, its value is `0` if `initialValue` is specified, otherwise `1`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] A value to which `accumulator` is initialized the first time the callback is called.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] If `initialValue` is specified, `callbackFn` starts executing with the first value in the array as `currentValue`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] If `initialValue` is *not* specified, `accumulator` is initialized to the first value in the array, and `callbackFn` starts executing with the second value in the array as `currentValue`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] In this case, if the array is empty (so that there's no first value to return as `accumulator`), an error is thrown.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The value that results from running the "reducer" callback function to completion over the entire array.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Thrown if the array contains no elements and `initialValue` is not provided.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The `reduce()` method is an iterative method.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] It runs a "reducer" callback function over all elements in the array, in ascending-index order, and accumulates them into a single value.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Every time, the return value of `callbackFn` is passed into `callbackFn` again on next invocation as `accumulator`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The final value of `accumulator` (which is the value returned from `callbackFn` on the final iteration of the array) becomes the return value of `reduce()`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Read the iterative methods section for more information about how these methods work in general.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] `callbackFn` is invoked only for array indexes which have assigned values.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] It is not invoked for empty slots in sparse arrays.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Unlike other iterative methods, `reduce()` does not accept a `thisArg` argument.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] `callbackFn` is always called with `undefined` as `this`, which gets substituted with `globalThis` if `callbackFn` is non-strict.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] `reduce()` is a central concept in functional programming, where it's not possible to mutate any value, so in order to accumulate all values in an array, one must return a new accumulator value on every iteration.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] This convention propagates to JavaScript's `reduce()`: you should use spreading or other copying methods where possible to create new arrays and objects as the accumulator, rather than mutating the existing one.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] If you decided to mutate the accumulator instead of copying it, remember to still return the modified object in the callback, or the next iteration will receive undefined.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] However, note that copying the accumulator may in turn lead to increased memory usage and degraded performance — see When to not use reduce() for more details.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] In such cases, to avoid bad performance and unreadable code, it's better to use a `for` loop instead.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] It only expects the `this` value to have a `length` property and integer-keyed properties.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] If the array only has one element (regardless of position) and no `initialValue` is provided, or if `initialValue` is provided but the array is empty, the solo value will be returned *without* calling `callbackFn`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] If `initialValue` is provided and the array is not empty, then the reduce method will always invoke the callback function starting at index 0.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The code below shows what happens if we call `reduce()` with an array and no initial value.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The `array` parameter never changes through the process — it's always `[15, 16, 17, 18, 19]`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The value returned by `reduce()` would be that of the last callback invocation (`85`).
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The value returned by `reduce()` in this case would be `95`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] To sum up the values contained in an array of objects, you **must** supply an `initialValue`, so that each item passes through your function.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The `pipe` function takes a sequence of functions and returns a new function.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] When the new function is called with an argument, the sequence of functions are called in order, which each one receiving the return value of the previous function.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Promise sequencing is essentially function piping demonstrated in the previous section, except done asynchronously.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] `reduce()` skips missing elements in sparse arrays, but it does not skip `undefined` values.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] The `reduce()` method reads the `length` property of `this` and then accesses each property whose key is a nonnegative integer less than `length`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Multipurpose higher-order functions like `reduce()` can be powerful but sometimes difficult to understand, especially for less-experienced JavaScript developers.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] If code becomes clearer when using other array methods, developers must weigh the readability tradeoff against the other benefits of using `reduce()`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] As previously stated, the reason why people may want to use `reduce()` is to mimic functional programming practices of immutable data.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] This code is ill-performing, because each iteration has to copy the entire `allNames` object, which could be big, depending how many unique names there are.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] This code has worst-case `O(N^2)` performance, where `N` is the length of `names`.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] A better alternative is to *mutate* the `allNames` object on each iteration.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Therefore, if your accumulator is an array or an object and you are copying the array or object on each iteration, you may accidentally introduce quadratic complexity into your code, causing performance to quickly degrade on large data.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] This has happened in real-world code — see for example Making Tanstack Table 1000x faster with a 1 line change.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] Some of the acceptable use cases of `reduce()` are given above (most notably, summing an array, promise sequencing, and function piping).
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] There are other cases where better alternatives than `reduce()` exist.
[src:ramda-functional/array-reduce] In cases where `reduce()` is the best choice, documentation and semantic variable naming can help mitigate readability drawbacks.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In mathematics and computer science, **currying** is the technique of translating a function that takes multiple arguments into a sequence of families of functions, each taking a single argument.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In this example, ${\mbox{curry}}$ itself becomes a function that takes f as an argument, and returns a function that maps each x to $f_{x}.$ The proper notation for expressing this is verbose.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] These definitions vary from context to context, and take different forms, depending on the theory that one is working in.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying is related to, but not the same as, partial application.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The example above can be used to illustrate partial application; it is quite similar.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The currying of a function with more than two arguments can be defined by induction.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying is useful in both practical and theoretical settings.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In functional programming languages, and many others, it provides a way of automatically managing how arguments are passed to functions and exceptions.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In theoretical computer science, it provides a way to study functions with multiple arguments in simpler theoretical models which provide only one argument.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The concept of currying was introduced by Gottlob Frege, developed by Moses Schönfinkel, and further developed by Haskell Curry.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying provides a way for working with functions that take multiple arguments, and using them in frameworks where functions might take only one argument.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] For example, some analytical techniques can only be applied to functions with a single argument.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Practical functions frequently take more arguments than this.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Frege showed that it was sufficient to provide solutions for the single argument case, as it was possible to transform a function with multiple arguments into a chain of single-argument functions instead.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] This transformation is the process now known as currying.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] All "ordinary" functions that might typically be encountered in mathematical analysis or in computer programming can be curried.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] However, there are categories in which currying is not possible; the most general categories which allow currying are the closed monoidal categories.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Some programming languages almost always use curried functions to achieve multiple arguments; notable examples are ML and Haskell, where in both cases all functions have exactly one argument.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] This property is inherited from lambda calculus, where multi-argument functions are usually represented in curried form.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying is related to, but not the same as partial application.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In practice, the programming technique of closures can be used to perform partial application and a kind of currying, by hiding arguments in an environment that travels with the curried function.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The "Curry" in "Currying" is a reference to logician Haskell Curry, who used the concept extensively, but Moses Schönfinkel had the idea six years before Curry.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The alternative name "Schönfinkelisation" has been proposed.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In the mathematical context, the principle can be traced back to work in 1893 by Frege.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The originator of the word "currying" is not clear.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Reynolds defined "currying" in a 1972 paper, but did not claim to have coined the term.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying is most easily understood by starting with an informal definition, which can then be molded to fit many different domains.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] First, there is some notation to be established.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The notation $X\to Y$ denotes all functions from X to Y .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] If f is such a function, we write $f\colon X\to Y$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Let $X\times Y$ denote the ordered pairs of the elements of X and Y respectively, that is, the Cartesian product of X and Y .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Here, X and Y may be sets, or they may be types, or they may be other kinds of objects, as explored below.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] That is, g takes an argument of type X and returns a function of type $Y\to Z$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In set theory, the notation $Y^{X}$ is used to denote the set of functions from the set X to the set Y .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying is the natural bijection between the set $A^{B\times C}$ of functions from $B\times C$ to A , and the set $(A^{C})^{B}$ of functions from B to the set of functions from C to A .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Indeed, it is this natural bijection that justifies the exponential notation for the set of functions.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] As is the case in all instances of currying, the formula above describes an adjoint pair of functors: for every fixed set C , the functor $B\mapsto B\times C$ is left adjoint to the functor $A\mapsto A^{C}$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In the category of sets, the object $Y^{X}$ is called the exponential object.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In the theory of function spaces, such as in functional analysis or homotopy theory, one is commonly interested in continuous functions between topological spaces.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] One writes ${\text{Hom}}(X,Y)$ (the Hom functor) for the set of *all* functions from X to Y , and uses the notation $Y^{X}$ to denote the subset of continuous functions.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] This is also the case when X , Y and $Y^{X}$ are compactly generated, although there are more cases.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] One useful corollary is that a function is continuous if and only if its curried form is continuous.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] is continuous when $Y^{X}$ is compact-open and Y locally compact Hausdorff.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] These two results are central for establishing the continuity of homotopy, i.e. when X is the unit interval I , so that $Z^{I\times Y}\cong (Z^{Y})^{I}$ can be thought of as either a homotopy of two functions from Y to Z , or, equivalently, a single (continuous) path in $Z^{Y}$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In algebraic topology, currying serves as an example of Eckmann–Hilton duality, and, as such, plays an important role in a variety of different settings.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] where $[A,B]$ is the set of homotopy classes of maps $A\rightarrow B$ , and $\Sigma A$ is the suspension of *A*, and $\Omega A$ is the loop space of *A*.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In essence, the suspension $\Sigma X$ can be seen as the cartesian product of X with the unit interval, modulo an equivalence relation to turn the interval into a loop.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The curried form then maps the space X to the space of functions from loops into Z , that is, from X into $\Omega Z$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Then ${\text{curry}}$ is the adjoint functor that maps suspensions to loop spaces, and uncurrying is the dual.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The duality between the mapping cone and the mapping fiber (cofibration and fibration) can be understood as a form of currying, which in turn leads to the duality of the long exact and coexact Puppe sequences.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In homological algebra, the relationship between currying and uncurrying is known as tensor-hom adjunction.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Here, an interesting twist arises: the Hom functor and the tensor product functor might not lift to an exact sequence; this leads to the definition of the Ext functor and the Tor functor.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In order theory, the theory of lattices of partially ordered sets, ${\text{curry}}$ is a continuous function when the lattice is given the Scott topology.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Scott-continuous functions were first investigated in the attempt to provide a semantics for lambda calculus (as ordinary set theory is inadequate to do this).
[src:ramda-functional/currying] More generally, Scott-continuous functions are now studied in domain theory, which encompasses the study of denotational semantics of computer algorithms.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Note that the Scott topology is quite different than many common topologies one might encounter in the category of topological spaces; the Scott topology is typically finer, and is not sober.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The notion of continuity makes its appearance in homotopy type theory, where, roughly speaking, two computer programs can be considered to be homotopic, i.e. compute the same results, if they can be "continuously" refactored from one to the other.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In theoretical computer science, currying provides a way to study functions with multiple arguments in very simple theoretical models, such as the lambda calculus, in which functions only take a single argument.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Consider a function $f(x,y)$ taking two arguments, and having the type $(X\times Y)\to Z$ , which should be understood to mean that *x* must have the type X , *y* must have the type Y , and the function itself returns the type Z .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] where $\lambda$ is the abstractor of lambda calculus.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The → operator is often considered right-associative, so the curried function type $X\to (Y\to Z)$ is often written as $X\to Y\to Z$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] That is, the parenthesis are not required to disambiguate the order of the application.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Curried functions may be used in any programming language that supports closures; however, uncurried functions are generally preferred for efficiency reasons, since the overhead of partial application and closure creation can then be avoided for most function calls.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In type theory, the general idea of a type system in computer science is formalized into a specific algebra of types.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] For example, when writing $f\colon X\to Y$ , the intent is that X and Y are types, while the arrow $\to$ is a type constructor, specifically, the function type or arrow type.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Similarly, the Cartesian product $X\times Y$ of types is constructed by the product type constructor $\times$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The type-theoretical approach is expressed in programming languages such as ML and the languages derived from and inspired by it: Caml, Haskell, and F#.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The type-theoretical approach provides a natural complement to the language of category theory, as discussed below.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] This is because categories, and specifically, monoidal categories, have an internal language, with simply typed lambda calculus being the most prominent example of such a language.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] It is important in this context, because it can be built from a single type constructor, the arrow type.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying then endows the language with a natural product type.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The correspondence between objects in categories and types then allows programming languages to be re-interpreted as logics (via Curry–Howard correspondence), and as other types of mathematical systems, as explored further, below.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The exponential object $Q^{P}$ in the category of Heyting algebras is normally written as material implication $P\to Q$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Distributive Heyting algebras are Boolean algebras, and the exponential object has the explicit form $\neg P\lor Q$ , thus making it clear that the exponential object really is material implication.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The above notions of currying and uncurrying find their most general, abstract statement in category theory.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying is a universal property of an exponential object, and gives rise to an adjunction in cartesian closed categories.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] That is, there is a natural isomorphism between the morphisms from a binary product $f\colon (X\times Y)\to Z$ and the morphisms to an exponential object $g\colon X\to Z^{Y}$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Here, *Hom* denotes the (external) Hom-functor of all morphisms in the category, while $B\Rightarrow C$ denotes the internal hom functor in the closed monoidal category.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] For the category of sets, the two are the same.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] When the product is the cartesian product, then the internal hom $B\Rightarrow C$ becomes the exponential object $C^{B}$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying can break down in one of two ways.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] One is if a category is not closed, and thus lacks an internal hom functor (possibly because there is more than one choice for such a functor).
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Another way is if it is not monoidal, and thus lacks a product (that is, lacks a way of writing down pairs of objects).
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Categories that do have both products and internal homs are exactly the closed monoidal categories.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The setting of cartesian closed categories is sufficient for the discussion of classical logic; the more general setting of closed monoidal categories is suitable for quantum computation.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The difference between these two is that the product for cartesian categories (such as the category of sets, complete partial orders or Heyting algebras) is just the Cartesian product; it is interpreted as an ordered pair of items (or a list).
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Simply typed lambda calculus is the internal language of cartesian closed categories; and it is for this reason that pairs and lists are the primary types in the type theory of LISP, Scheme and many functional programming languages.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] By contrast, the product for monoidal categories (such as Hilbert space and the vector spaces of functional analysis) is the tensor product.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The internal language of such categories is linear logic, a form of quantum logic; the corresponding type system is the linear type system.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Such categories are suitable for describing entangled quantum states, and, more generally, allow a vast generalization of the Curry–Howard correspondence to quantum mechanics, to cobordisms in algebraic topology, and to string theory.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The linear type system, and linear logic are useful for describing synchronization primitives, such as mutual exclusion locks, and the operation of vending machines.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Currying and partial function application are often conflated.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] One of the significant differences between the two is that a call to a partially applied function returns the result right away, not another function down the currying chain; this distinction can be illustrated clearly for functions whose arity is greater than two.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Given a function of type $f\colon (X\times Y\times Z)\to N$ , currying produces ${\text{curry}}(f)\colon X\to (Y\to (Z\to N))$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] That is, while an evaluation of the first function might be represented as $f(1,2,3)$ , evaluation of the curried function would be represented as $f_{\text{curried}}(1)(2)(3)$ , applying each argument in turn to a single-argument function returned by the previous invocation.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Note that after calling $f_{\text{curried}}(1)$ , we are left with a function that takes a single argument and returns another function, not a function that takes two arguments.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] In contrast, **partial function application** refers to the process of fixing a number of arguments to a function, producing another function of smaller arity.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Given the definition of f above, we might fix (or 'bind') the first argument, producing a function of type ${\text{partial}}(f)\colon (Y\times Z)\to N$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Evaluation of this function might be represented as $f_{\text{partial}}(2,3)$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Note that the result of partial function application in this case is a function that takes two arguments.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Intuitively, partial function application says "if you fix the first argument of the function, you get a function of the remaining arguments".
[src:ramda-functional/currying] For example, if function *div* stands for the division operation *x*/*y*, then *div* with the parameter *x* fixed at 1 (i.e., *div* 1) is another function: the same as the function *inv* that returns the multiplicative inverse of its argument, defined by *inv*(*y*) = 1/*y*.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] The practical motivation for partial application is that very often the functions obtained by supplying some but not all of the arguments to a function are useful; for example, many languages have a function or operator similar to `plus_one`.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Partial application makes it easy to define these functions, for example by creating a function that represents the addition operator with 1 bound as its first argument.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Thus, partial application is reduced to a curried function at a fixed point.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Further, a curried function at a fixed point is (trivially), a partial application.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] For further evidence, note that, given any function $f(x,y)$ , a function $g(y,x)$ may be defined such that $g(y,x)=f(x,y)$ .
[src:ramda-functional/currying] Thus, any partial application may be reduced to a single curry operation.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] As such, curry is more suitably defined as an operation which, in many theoretical cases, is often applied recursively, but which is theoretically indistinguishable (when considered as an operation) from a partial application.
[src:ramda-functional/currying] So, a partial application can be defined as the objective result of a single application of the curry operator on some ordering of the inputs of some function.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In computer science, **functional programming** is a programming paradigm where programs are constructed by applying and composing functions.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] It is a declarative programming paradigm in which function definitions are trees of expressions that map values to other values, rather than a sequence of imperative statements which update the running state of the program.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In functional programming, functions are treated as first-class entities, meaning that they can be bound to names (including local identifiers), passed as arguments, and returned from other functions, just as any other data type can.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This allows programs to be written in a declarative and composable style, where small functions are combined in a modular manner.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming is sometimes treated as synonymous with purely functional programming, a subset of functional programming that treats all functions as deterministic mathematical functions, or pure functions.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] When a pure function is called with some given arguments, it will always return the same result, and cannot be affected by any mutable state or other side effects.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This is in contrast with impure procedures, common in imperative programming, which can have side effects (such as modifying the program's state or taking input from a user).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Proponents of purely functional programming claim that by restricting side effects, programs can have fewer bugs, be easier to debug and test, and be more suited to formal verification.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming has its roots in academia, evolving from the lambda calculus, a formal system of computation based only on functions.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming has historically been less popular than imperative programming, but many functional languages are seeing use today in industry and education, including Common Lisp, Scheme, Clojure, Wolfram Language, Racket, Erlang, Elixir, OCaml, Haskell, and F#.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Lean is a functional programming language commonly used for verifying mathematical theorems.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming is also key to some languages that have found success in specific domains, like JavaScript in the Web, R in statistics, J, K and Q in financial analysis, and XQuery/XSLT for XML.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Domain-specific declarative languages like SQL and Lex/Yacc use some elements of functional programming, such as not allowing mutable values.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In addition, many other programming languages support programming in a functional style or have implemented features from functional programming, such as C++ (since C++11), C#, Kotlin, Perl, PHP, Python, Go, Rust, Raku, Scala, and Java (since Java 8).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The lambda calculus, developed in the 1930s by Alonzo Church, is a formal system of computation built from function application.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In 1937 Alan Turing proved that the lambda calculus and Turing machines are equivalent models of computation, showing that the lambda calculus is Turing complete.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Lambda calculus forms the basis of all functional programming languages.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] An equivalent theoretical formulation, combinatory logic, was developed by Moses Schönfinkel and Haskell Curry in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Church later developed a weaker system, the simply typed lambda calculus, which extended the lambda calculus by assigning a data type to all terms.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This forms the basis for statically typed functional programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The first high-level functional programming language, Lisp, was developed in the late 1950s for the IBM 700/7000 series of scientific computers by John McCarthy while at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Lisp functions were defined using Church's lambda notation, extended with a label construct to allow recursive functions.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Lisp first introduced many paradigmatic features of functional programming, though early Lisps were multi-paradigm languages, and incorporated support for numerous programming styles as new paradigms evolved.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Later dialects, such as Scheme and Clojure, and offshoots such as Dylan and Julia, sought to simplify and rationalise Lisp around a cleanly functional core, while Common Lisp was designed to preserve and update the paradigmatic features of the numerous older dialects it replaced.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Information Processing Language (IPL), 1956, is sometimes cited as the first computer-based functional programming language.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] It is an assembly-style language for manipulating lists of symbols.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] It does have a notion of *generator*, which amounts to a function that accepts a function as an argument, and, since it is a low-level programming language, code can be data, so IPL can be regarded as having higher-order functions.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] However, it relies heavily on the mutating list structure and similar imperative features.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Iverson developed APL in the early 1960s, described in his 1962 book *A Programming Language* (ISBN 9780471430148).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] APL was the primary influence on John Backus's FP.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In the early 1990s, Iverson and Roger Hui created J.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In the mid-1990s, Arthur Whitney, who had previously worked with Iverson, created K, which is used commercially in financial industries along with its descendant Q.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In the mid-1960s, Peter Landin invented SECD machine, the first abstract machine for a functional programming language, described a correspondence between ALGOL 60 and the lambda calculus, and proposed the ISWIM programming language.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] John Backus presented FP in his 1977 Turing Award lecture "Can Programming Be Liberated From the von Neumann Style?
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] A Functional Style and its Algebra of Programs".
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] He defines functional programs as being built up in a hierarchical way by means of "combining forms" that allow an "algebra of programs"; in modern language, this means that functional programs follow the principle of compositionality.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Backus's paper popularized research into functional programming, though it emphasized function-level programming rather than the lambda-calculus style now associated with functional programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The 1973 language ML was created by Robin Milner at the University of Edinburgh, and David Turner developed the language SASL at the University of St Andrews.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Also in Edinburgh in the 1970s, Burstall and Darlington developed the functional language NPL.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] NPL was based on Kleene Recursion Equations and was first introduced in their work on program transformation.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Burstall, MacQueen and Sannella then incorporated the polymorphic type checking from ML to produce the language Hope.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] ML eventually developed into several dialects, the most common of which are now OCaml and Standard ML.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Steele and Gerald Jay Sussman developed Scheme, as described in the Lambda Papers and the 1985 textbook *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs*.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Scheme was the first dialect of lisp to use lexical scoping and to require tail-call optimization, features that encourage functional programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In the 1980s, Per Martin-Löf developed intuitionistic type theory (also called *constructive* type theory), which associated functional programs with constructive proofs expressed as dependent types.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This led to new approaches to interactive theorem proving and has influenced the development of subsequent functional programming languages.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The lazy functional language, Miranda, developed by David Turner, initially appeared in 1985 and had a strong influence on Haskell.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] With Miranda being proprietary, Haskell began with a consensus in 1987 to form an open standard for functional programming research; implementation releases have been ongoing as of 1990.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] More recently it has found use in niches such as parametric CAD in the OpenSCAD language built on the CGAL framework, although its restriction on reassigning values (all values are treated as constants) has led to confusion among users who are unfamiliar with functional programming as a concept.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming continues to be used in commercial settings.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] A number of concepts and paradigms are specific to functional programming, and generally foreign to imperative programming (including object-oriented programming).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] However, programming languages often cater to several programming paradigms, so programmers using "mostly imperative" languages may have utilized some of these concepts.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are functions that can either take other functions as arguments or return them as results.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In calculus, an example of a higher-order function is the differential operator $d/dx$ , which returns the derivative of a function f .
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are closely related to first-class functions in that higher-order functions and first-class functions both allow functions as arguments and results of other functions.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Higher-order functions enable partial application or currying, a technique that applies a function to its arguments one at a time, with each application returning a new function that accepts the next argument.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This lets a programmer succinctly express, for example, the successor function as the addition operator partially applied to the natural number one.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Pure functions (or expressions) have no side effects (memory or I/O).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Some compilers, such as gcc, add extra keywords for a programmer to explicitly mark external functions as pure, to enable such optimizations.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Fortran 95 also lets functions be designated *pure*.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] C++11 added `constexpr` keyword with similar semantics.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Iteration (looping) in functional languages is usually accomplished via recursion.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Recursive functions invoke themselves, letting an operation be repeated until it reaches the base case.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In general, recursion requires maintaining a stack, which consumes space in a linear amount to the depth of recursion.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This could make recursion prohibitively expensive to use instead of imperative loops.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] However, a special form of recursion known as tail recursion can be recognized and optimized by a compiler into the same code used to implement iteration in imperative languages.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Tail recursion optimization can be implemented by transforming the program into continuation passing style during compiling, among other approaches.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The Scheme language standard requires implementations to support proper tail recursion, meaning they must allow an unbounded number of active tail calls.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Proper tail recursion is not simply an optimization; it is a language feature that assures users that they can use recursion to express a loop and doing so would be safe-for-space.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Moreover, contrary to its name, it accounts for all tail calls, not just tail recursion.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] While proper tail recursion is usually implemented by turning code into imperative loops, implementations might implement it in other ways.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] For example, Chicken intentionally maintains a stack and lets the stack overflow.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] However, when this happens, its garbage collector will claim space back, allowing an unbounded number of active tail calls even though it does not turn tail recursion into a loop.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Common patterns of recursion can be abstracted away using higher-order functions, with catamorphisms and anamorphisms (or "folds" and "unfolds") being the most obvious examples.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Such recursion schemes play a role analogous to built-in control structures such as loops in imperative languages.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Some special purpose languages such as Rocq allow only well-founded recursion and are strongly normalizing (nonterminating computations can be expressed only with infinite streams of values called codata).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] As a consequence, these languages fail to be Turing complete and expressing certain functions in them is impossible, but they can still express a wide class of interesting computations while avoiding the problems introduced by unrestricted recursion.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming limited to well-founded recursion with a few other constraints is called total functional programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional languages can be categorized by whether they use *strict (eager)* or *non-strict (lazy)* evaluation, concepts that refer to how function arguments are processed when an expression is being evaluated.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The technical difference is in the denotational semantics of expressions containing failing or divergent computations.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Under strict evaluation, the evaluation of any term containing a failing subterm fails.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] fails under strict evaluation because of the division by zero in the third element of the list.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Under lazy evaluation, the length function returns the value 4 (i.e., the number of items in the list), since evaluating it does not attempt to evaluate the terms making up the list.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In brief, strict evaluation always fully evaluates function arguments before invoking the function.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation does not evaluate function arguments unless their values are required to evaluate the function call itself.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The usual implementation strategy for lazy evaluation in functional languages is graph reduction.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation is used by default in several pure functional languages, including Miranda, Clean, and Haskell.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Hughes 1984 argues for lazy evaluation as a mechanism for improving program modularity through separation of concerns, by easing independent implementation of producers and consumers of data streams.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Launchbury 1993 describes some difficulties that lazy evaluation introduces, particularly in analyzing a program's storage requirements, and proposes an operational semantics to aid in such analysis.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Harper 2009 proposes including both strict and lazy evaluation in the same language, using the language's type system to distinguish them.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Some research-oriented functional languages such as Rocq, Agda, Cayenne, and Epigram are based on intuitionistic type theory, which lets types depend on terms.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] These type systems do not have decidable type inference and are difficult to understand and program with.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] But dependent types can express arbitrary propositions in higher-order logic.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Through the Curry–Howard isomorphism, then, well-typed programs in these languages become a means of writing formal mathematical proofs from which a compiler can generate certified code.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] While these languages are mainly of interest in academic research (including in formalized mathematics), they have begun to be used in engineering as well.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Compcert is a compiler for a subset of the language C that is written in Rocq and formally verified.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] A limited form of dependent types called generalized algebraic data types (GADT's) can be implemented in a way that provides some of the benefits of dependently typed programming while avoiding most of its inconvenience.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] GADT's are available in the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, in OCaml and in Scala, and have been proposed as additions to other languages including Java and C#.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programs do not have assignment statements, that is, the value of a variable in a functional program never changes once defined.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This eliminates any chances of side effects because any variable can be replaced with its actual value at any point of execution.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] So, functional programs are referentially transparent.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Consider C assignment statement `x = x * 10`, this changes the value assigned to the variable `x`.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Let us say that the initial value of `x` was `1`, then two consecutive evaluations of the variable `x` yields `10` and `100` respectively.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Clearly, replacing `x = x * 10` with either `10` or `100` gives a program a different meaning, and so the expression *is not* referentially transparent.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In fact, assignment statements are never referentially transparent.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Now, consider another function such as `int plusOne(int x) { return x + 1; }` *is* transparent, as it does not implicitly change the input x and thus has no such side effects.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programs exclusively use this type of function and are therefore referentially transparent.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way to their imperative counterparts.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] For example, the array with constant access and update times is a basic component of most imperative languages, and many imperative data-structures, such as the hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by maps or random access lists, which admit purely functional implementation, but have logarithmic access and update times.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Purely functional data structures have persistence, a property of keeping previous versions of the data structure unmodified.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In Clojure, persistent data structures are used as functional alternatives to their imperative counterparts.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Persistent vectors, for example, use trees for partial updating.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Calling the insert method will result in some but not all nodes being created.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming is very different from imperative programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The most significant differences stem from the fact that functional programming avoids side effects, which are used in imperative programming to implement state and I/O.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Pure functional programming completely prevents side-effects and provides referential transparency.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Higher-order functions are rarely used in older imperative programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] A traditional imperative program might use a loop to traverse and modify a list.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] A functional program, on the other hand, would probably use a higher-order "map" function that takes a function and a list, generating and returning a new list by applying the function to each list item.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The following two examples (written in Java) achieve the same effect: they multiply all even numbers in an array by 10 and add them all, storing the final sum in the variable `result`.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Sometimes the abstractions offered by functional programming might lead to development of more robust code that avoids certain issues that might arise when building upon large amount of complex, imperative code, such as off-by-one errors (see Greenspun's tenth rule).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] There are tasks (for example, maintaining a bank account balance) that often seem most naturally implemented with state.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Pure functional programming performs these tasks, and I/O tasks such as accepting user input and printing to the screen, in a different way.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The pure functional programming language Haskell implements them using monads, derived from category theory.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Monads offer a way to abstract certain types of computational patterns, including (but not limited to) modeling of computations with mutable state (and other side effects such as I/O) in an imperative manner without losing purity.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] While existing monads may be easy to apply in a program, given appropriate templates and examples, many students find them difficult to understand conceptually, e.g., when asked to define new monads (which is sometimes needed for certain types of libraries).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional languages also simulate states by passing around immutable states.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This can be done by making a function accept the state as one of its parameters, and return a new state together with the result, leaving the old state unchanged.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Impure functional languages usually include a more direct method of managing mutable state.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Clojure, for example, uses managed references that can be updated by applying pure functions to the current state.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This kind of approach enables mutability while still promoting the use of pure functions as the preferred way to express computations.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Alternative methods such as Hoare logic and uniqueness have been developed to track side effects in programs.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Some modern research languages use effect systems to make the presence of side effects explicit.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming languages are typically less efficient in their use of CPU and memory than imperative languages such as C and Pascal.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This is related to the fact that some mutable data structures like arrays have a very straightforward implementation using present hardware.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Flat arrays may be accessed very efficiently with deeply pipelined CPUs, prefetched efficiently through caches (with no complex pointer chasing), or handled with SIMD instructions.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] It is also not easy to create their equally efficient general-purpose immutable counterparts.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] For purely functional languages, the worst-case slowdown is logarithmic in the number of memory cells used, because mutable memory can be represented by a purely functional data structure with logarithmic access time (such as a balanced tree).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] However, such slowdowns are not universal.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] For programs that perform intensive numerical computations, functional languages such as OCaml and Clean are only slightly slower than C according to The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] For programs that handle large matrices and multidimensional databases, array functional languages (such as J and K) were designed with speed optimizations.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Immutability of data can in many cases lead to execution efficiency by allowing the compiler to make assumptions that are unsafe in an imperative language, thus increasing opportunities for inline expansion.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Even if the involved copying that may seem implicit when dealing with persistent immutable data structures might seem computationally costly, some functional programming languages, like Clojure solve this issue by implementing mechanisms for safe memory sharing between *formally* *immutable* data.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This is how for example `java.util.concurrent` classes are implemented, where some of them are immutable variants of the corresponding classes that are not suitable for concurrent use.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming languages often have a concurrency model that instead of shared state and synchronization, leverages message passing mechanisms (such as the actor model, where each actor is a container for state, behavior, child actors and a message queue).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This approach is common in Erlang/Elixir or Akka.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Lazy evaluation may also speed up the program, even asymptotically, whereas it may slow it down at most by a constant factor (however, it may introduce memory leaks if used improperly).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Launchbury 1993 discusses theoretical issues related to memory leaks from lazy evaluation, and O'Sullivan *et al.* 2008 give some practical advice for analyzing and fixing them.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] However, the most general implementations of lazy evaluation making extensive use of dereferenced code and data perform poorly on modern processors with deep pipelines and multi-level caches (where a cache miss may cost hundreds of cycles).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Some functional programming languages might not optimize abstractions such as higher order functions like "map" or "filter" as efficiently as the underlying imperative operations.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] has the mean execution time of 4.76 ms, while the second one, in which `.equals` is a direct invocation of the underlying Java method, has a mean execution time of 2.8 μs – roughly 1700 times faster.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Part of that can be attributed to the type checking and exception handling involved in the implementation of `even?`.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] For instance the lo library for Go, which implements various higher-order functions common in functional programming languages using generics.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In a benchmark provided by the library's author, calling `map` is 4% slower than an equivalent `for` loop and has the same allocation profile, which can be attributed to various compiler optimizations, such as inlining.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] One distinguishing feature of Rust are *zero-cost abstractions*.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This means that using them imposes no additional runtime overhead.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] This is achieved thanks to the compiler using loop unrolling, where each iteration of a loop, be it imperative or using iterators, is converted into a standalone Assembly instruction, without the overhead of the loop controlling code.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] If an iterative operation writes to an array, the resulting array's elements will be stored in specific CPU registers, allowing for constant-time access at runtime.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] It is possible to use a functional style of programming in languages that are not traditionally considered functional languages.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] For example, both D and Fortran 95 explicitly support pure functions.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] JavaScript, Lua, Python and Go had first class functions from their inception.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Python had support for "lambda", "map", "reduce", and "filter" in 1994, as well as closures in Python 2.2, though Python 3 relegated "reduce" to the `functools` standard library module.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] First-class functions have been introduced into other mainstream languages such as Perl 5.0 in 1994, PHP 5.3, Visual Basic 9, C# 3.0, C++11, and Kotlin.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In Perl, lambda, map, reduce, filter, and closures are fully supported and frequently used.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The book Higher-Order Perl, released in 2005, was written to provide an expansive guide on using Perl for functional programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In PHP, anonymous classes, closures and lambdas are fully supported.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Libraries and language extensions for immutable data structures are being developed to aid programming in the functional style.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In Java, anonymous classes can sometimes be used to simulate closures; however, anonymous classes are not always proper replacements to closures because they have more limited capabilities.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Java 8 supports lambda expressions as a replacement for some anonymous classes.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In C#, anonymous classes are not necessary, because closures and lambdas are fully supported.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Libraries and language extensions for immutable data structures are being developed to aid programming in the functional style in C#.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Many object-oriented design patterns are expressible in functional programming terms: for example, the strategy pattern simply dictates use of a higher-order function, and the visitor pattern roughly corresponds to a catamorphism, or fold.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Similarly, the idea of immutable data from functional programming is often included in imperative programming languages, for example the tuple in Python, which is an immutable array, and Object.freeze() in JavaScript.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Logic programming can be viewed as a generalisation of functional programming, in which functions are a special case of relations.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] For example, the function, mother(X) = Y, (every X has only one mother Y) can be represented by the relation mother(X, Y).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Whereas functions have a strict input-output pattern of arguments, relations can be queried with any pattern of inputs and outputs.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Compared with relational syntax, functional syntax is a more compact notation for nested functions.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] However, the difference between the two representations is simply syntactic.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Ciao transforms the function-like notation into relational form and executes the resulting logic program using the standard Prolog execution strategy.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Emacs, a highly extensible text editor family uses its own Lisp dialect for writing plugins.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] The original author of the most popular Emacs implementation, GNU Emacs and Emacs Lisp, Richard Stallman considers Lisp one of his favorite programming languages.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Spreadsheets can be considered a form of pure, zeroth-order, strict-evaluation functional programming system.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] However, spreadsheets generally lack higher-order functions as well as code reuse, and in some implementations, also lack recursion.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Several extensions have been developed for spreadsheet programs to enable higher-order and reusable functions, but so far remain primarily academic in nature.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Due to their composability, functional programming paradigms can be suitable for microservices-based architectures.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming is an active area of research in the field of programming language theory.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] There are several peer-reviewed publication venues focusing on functional programming, including the International Conference on Functional Programming, the Journal of Functional Programming, and the Symposium on Trends in Functional Programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming has been employed in a wide range of industrial applications.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Scheme, a dialect of Lisp, was used as the basis for several applications on early Apple Macintosh computers and has been applied to problems such as training-simulation software and telescope control.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] OCaml, which was introduced in the mid-1990s, has seen commercial use in areas such as financial analysis, driver verification, industrial robot programming and static analysis of embedded software.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Haskell, though initially intended as a research language, has also been applied in areas such as aerospace systems, hardware design and web programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Other functional programming languages that have seen use in industry include Scala, F#, Wolfram Language, Lisp, Standard ML and Clojure.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Scala has been widely used in Data science, while ClojureScript, Elm or PureScript are some of the functional frontend programming languages used in production.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional "platforms" have been popular in finance for risk analytics (particularly with large investment banks).
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Risk factors are coded as functions that form interdependent graphs (categories) to measure correlations in market shifts, similar in manner to Gröbner basis optimizations but also for regulatory frameworks such as Comprehensive Capital Analysis and Review.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Given the use of OCaml and Caml variations in finance, these systems are sometimes considered related to a categorical abstract machine.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Functional programming is heavily influenced by category theory.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Many universities teach functional programming.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Some treat it as an introductory programming concept while others first teach imperative programming methods.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] Outside of computer science, functional programming is used to teach problem-solving, algebraic and geometric concepts.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] It has also been used to teach classical mechanics, as in the book *Structure and Interpretation of Classical Mechanics*.
[src:ramda-functional/functional-programming] In particular, Scheme has been a relatively popular choice for teaching programming for years.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] All other functions are *first-order functions*.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] In mathematics higher-order functions are also termed *operators* or *functionals*.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] The differential operator in calculus is a common example, since it maps a function to its derivative, also a function.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Higher-order functions should not be confused with other uses of the word "functor" throughout mathematics, see Functor (disambiguation).
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] In the untyped lambda calculus, all functions are higher-order; in a typed lambda calculus, from which most functional programming languages are derived, higher-order functions that take one function as argument are values with types of the form $(\tau _{1}\to \tau _{2})\to \tau _{3}$ .
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] In the following examples, the higher-order function `twice` takes a function, and applies the function to some value twice.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] If `twice` has to be applied several times for the same `f` it preferably should return a function rather than a value.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] This is in line with the "don't repeat yourself" principle.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Alternatively, we can also compose using pure anonymous functions.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] In this Erlang example, the higher-order function `or_else/2` takes a list of functions (`Fs`) and argument (`X`).
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] It evaluates the function `F` with the argument `X` as argument.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] If the function `F` returns false then the next function in `Fs` will be evaluated.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] If the function `F` returns `{false, Y}` then the next function in `Fs` with argument `Y` will be evaluated.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] If the function `F` returns `R` the higher-order function `or_else/2` will return `R`.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Note that `X`, `Y`, and `R` can be functions.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Notice a function literal can be defined either with an identifier (`twice`) or anonymously (assigned to variable `plusThree`).
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Note that arrow functions implicitly capture any variables that come from the parent scope, whereas anonymous functions require the `use` keyword to do the same.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Python decorator syntax is often used to replace a function with the result of passing that function through a higher-order function.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] In Raku, all code objects are closures and therefore can reference inner "lexical" variables from an outer scope because the lexical variable is "closed" inside of the function.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Raku also supports "pointy block" syntax for lambda expressions which can be assigned to a variable or invoked anonymously.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Tcl uses apply command to apply an anonymous function (since 8.6).
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] The XACML standard defines higher-order functions in the standard to apply a function to multiple values of attribute bags.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] The list of higher-order functions in XACML can be found here.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Function pointers in languages such as C, C++, Fortran, and Pascal allow programmers to pass around references to functions.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] The qsort function from the C standard library uses a function pointer to emulate the behavior of a higher-order function.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Macros can also be used to achieve some of the effects of higher-order functions.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] However, macros cannot easily avoid the problem of variable capture; they may also result in large amounts of duplicated code, which can be more difficult for a compiler to optimize.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Macros are generally not strongly typed, although they may produce strongly typed code.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] In other imperative programming languages, it is possible to achieve some of the same algorithmic results as are obtained via higher-order functions by dynamically executing code (sometimes called *Eval* or *Execute* operations) in the scope of evaluation.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] In object-oriented programming languages that do not support higher-order functions, objects can be an effective substitute.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] An object's methods act in essence like functions, and a method may accept objects as parameters and produce objects as return values.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Objects often carry added run-time overhead compared to pure functions, however, and added boilerplate code for defining and instantiating an object and its method(s).
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] Languages that permit stack-based (versus heap-based) objects or structs can provide more flexibility with this method.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] The function `a()` takes a `Txy` record as input and returns the integer value of the sum of the record's `x` and `y` fields (3 + 7).
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] In this case, different types are used to trigger different functions via function overloading.
[src:ramda-functional/higher-order-function] The overloaded function in this example has the signature `auto apply`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A special placeholder value used to specify "gaps" within curried functions, allowing partial application of any combination of arguments, regardless of their positions.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Creates a new list iteration function from an existing one by adding two new parameters to its callback function: the current index, and the entire list.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] This would turn, for instance, `R.map` function into one that more closely resembles `Array.prototype.map`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Note that this will only work for functions in which the iteration callback function is the first parameter, and where the list is the last parameter.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] As with `addIndex`, `addIndexRight` creates a new list iteration function from an existing one by adding two new parameters to its callback function: the current index, and the entire list.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Unlike `addIndex`, `addIndexRight` iterates from the right to the left.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A copy of the supplied array-like object with the element at index `idx` replaced with the value returned by applying `fn` to the existing element.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Applies a function to the value at the given index of an array, returning a new copy of the array with the element at the given index replaced with the result of the function application.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] When `idx < -list.length || idx >= list.length`, the original list is returned.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] `true` if the predicate is satisfied by every element, `false` otherwise.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns `true` if all elements of the list match the predicate, `false` if there are any that don't.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to the `all` method of the second argument, if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Acts as a transducer if a transformer is given in list position.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Takes a list of predicates and returns a predicate that returns true for a given list of arguments if every one of the provided predicates is satisfied by those arguments.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The function returned is a curried function whose arity matches that of the highest-arity predicate.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a function that always returns the given value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Note that for non-primitives the value returned is a reference to the original value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] This function is known as `const`, `constant`, or `K` (for K combinator) in other languages and libraries.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns the first argument if it is falsy, otherwise the second argument.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Acts as the boolean `and` statement if both inputs are `Boolean`s.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns the result of applying the onSuccess function to the value inside a successfully resolved promise.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] This is useful for working with promises inside function compositions.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] `true` if the predicate is satisfied by at least one element, `false` otherwise.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns `true` if at least one of the elements of the list match the predicate, `false` otherwise.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to the `any` method of the second argument, if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Takes a list of predicates and returns a predicate that returns true for a given list of arguments if at least one of the provided predicates is satisfied by those arguments.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] ap applies a list of functions to a list of values.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to the `ap` method of the first argument, if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Also treats curried functions as applicatives.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a new list, composed of n-tuples of consecutive elements.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] If `n` is greater than the length of the list, an empty list is returned.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A new list containing the elements of the old list followed by `el`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a new list containing the contents of the given list, followed by the given element.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Applies function `fn` to the argument list `args`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] This is useful for creating a fixed-arity function from a variadic function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] `fn` should be a bound function if context is significant.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A function that returns an object of the same structure as `spec', with each property set to the value returned by calling its associated function with the supplied arguments.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Given a spec object recursively mapping properties to functions, creates a function producing an object of the same structure, by mapping each property to the result of calling its associated function with the supplied arguments.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Takes a value and applies a function to it.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] This function is also known as the `thrush` combinator.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Makes an ascending comparator function out of a function that returns a value that can be compared with `<` and `>`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Makes an ascending comparator function out of a function that returns a value that can be compared with natural sorting using localeCompare.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A new object equivalent to the original except for the changed property.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Makes a shallow clone of an object, setting or overriding the specified property with the given value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Note that this copies and flattens prototype properties onto the new object as well.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] All non-primitive properties are copied by reference.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A new object equivalent to the original except along the specified path.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Makes a shallow clone of an object, setting or overriding the nodes required to create the given path, and placing the specific value at the tail end of that path.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The new function is guaranteed to be of arity 2.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Wraps a function of any arity (including nullary) in a function that accepts exactly 2 parameters.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Any extraneous parameters will not be passed to the supplied function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A function that will execute in the context of `thisObj`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Creates a function that is bound to a context.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Note: `R.bind` does not provide the additional argument-binding capabilities of Function.prototype.bind.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] a function that applies its arguments to `f` and `g` and `&&`s their outputs together.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A function which calls the two provided functions and returns the `&&` of the results.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] It returns the result of the first function if it is false-y and the result of the second function otherwise.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Note that this is short-circuited, meaning that the second function will not be invoked if the first returns a false-y value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] In addition to functions, `R.both` also accepts any fantasy-land compatible applicative functor.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns the result of calling its first argument with the remaining arguments.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] This is occasionally useful as a converging function for `R.converge`: the first branch can produce a function while the remaining branches produce values to be passed to that function as its arguments.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] `chain` maps a function over a list and concatenates the results.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] `chain` is also known as `flatMap` in some libraries.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to the `chain` method of the second argument, if present, according to the FantasyLand Chain spec.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] If second argument is a function, `chain(f, g)(x)` is equivalent to `f(g(x), x)`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Restricts a number to be within a range.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Also works for other ordered types such as Strings and Dates.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Creates a deep copy of the source that can be used in place of the source object without retaining any references to it.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The source object may contain (nested) `Array`s and `Object`s, `Number`s, `String`s, `Boolean`s and `Date`s.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] `Function`s are assigned by reference rather than copied.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to a `clone` method if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Note that if the source object has multiple nodes that share a reference, the returned object will have the same structure, but the references will be pointed to the location within the cloned value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] An array of arrays where each sub-array contains items for which the String-returning function has returned the same value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Splits a list into sub-lists, based on the result of calling a key-returning function on each element, and grouping the results according to values returned.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Makes a comparator function out of a function that reports whether the first element is less than the second.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Takes a function `f` and returns a function `g` such that if called with the same arguments when `f` returns a "truthy" value, `g` returns `false` and when `f` returns a "falsy" value `g` returns `true`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Performs right-to-left function composition.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The last argument may have any arity; the remaining arguments must be unary.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Performs right-to-left function composition using transforming function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The last function may have any arity; the remaining functions must be unary.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Unlike `compose`, functions are passed in an array.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A list consisting of the elements of `firstList` followed by the elements of `secondList`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns the result of concatenating the given lists or strings.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Note: `R.concat` expects both arguments to be of the same type, unlike the native `Array.prototype.concat` method.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] It will throw an error if you `concat` an Array with a non-Array value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to the `concat` method of the first argument, if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Can also concatenate two members of a fantasy-land compatible semigroup.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a function, `fn`, which encapsulates `if/else, if/else, ...` logic.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] `R.cond` takes a list of [predicate, transformer] pairs.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] All of the arguments to `fn` are applied to each of the predicates in turn until one returns a "truthy" value, at which point `fn` returns the result of applying its arguments to the corresponding transformer.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] If none of the predicates matches, `fn` returns undefined.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A wrapped, curried constructor function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Wraps a constructor function inside a curried function that can be called with the same arguments and returns the same type.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The arity of the function returned is specified to allow using variadic constructor functions.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Accepts a converging function and a list of branching functions and returns a new function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The arity of the new function is the same as the arity of the longest branching function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] When invoked, this new function is applied to some arguments, and each branching function is applied to those same arguments.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The results of each branching function are passed as arguments to the converging function to produce the return value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The count of items matching the predicate.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] An object mapping keys to number of occurrences in the list.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Counts the elements of a list according to how many match each value of a key generated by the supplied function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns an object mapping the keys produced by `fn` to the number of occurrences in the list.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Note that all keys are coerced to strings because of how JavaScript objects work.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a curried equivalent of the provided function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The curried function has two unusual capabilities.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] First, its arguments needn't be provided one at a time.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Secondly, the special placeholder value `R.__` may be used to specify "gaps", allowing partial application of any combination of arguments, regardless of their positions.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Please note that default parameters don't count towards a function arity and therefore `curry` won't work well with those.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a curried equivalent of the provided function, with the specified arity.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns the second argument if it is not `null`, `undefined` or `NaN`; otherwise the first argument is returned.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Makes a descending comparator function out of a function that returns a value that can be compared with `<` and `>`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Makes a descending comparator function out of a function that returns a value that can be compared with natural sorting using localeCompare.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The elements in `list1` that are not in `list2`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Finds the set (i.e. no duplicates) of all elements in the first list not contained in the second list.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Objects and Arrays are compared in terms of value equality, not reference equality.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Duplication is determined according to the value returned by applying the supplied predicate to two list elements.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a new object that does not contain a `prop` property.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Makes a shallow clone of an object, omitting the property at the given path.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns all but the first `n` elements of the given list, string, or transducer/transformer (or object with a `drop` method).
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to the `drop` method of the second argument, if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a list containing all but the last `n` elements of the given `list`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A new array without any trailing elements that return `falsy` values from the `predicate`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a new list excluding all the tailing elements of a given list which satisfy the supplied predicate function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] It passes each value from the right to the supplied predicate function, skipping elements until the predicate function returns a `falsy` value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The predicate function is applied to one argument: *(value)*.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a new list without any consecutively repeating elements.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] `R.equals` is used to determine equality.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a new list without any consecutively repeating elements, based upon the value returned by applying the supplied function to each list element.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Equality is determined by applying the supplied predicate to each pair of consecutive elements.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] The first element in a series of equal elements will be preserved.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns a new list excluding the leading elements of a given list which satisfy the supplied predicate function.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] It passes each value to the supplied predicate function, skipping elements while the predicate function returns `true`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to the `dropWhile` method of the second argument, if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] a function that applies its arguments to `f` and `g` and `||`s their outputs together.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A function wrapping calls to the two functions in an `||` operation, returning the result of the first function if it is truth-y and the result of the second function otherwise.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Note that this is short-circuited, meaning that the second function will not be invoked if the first returns a truth-y value.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] In addition to functions, `R.either` also accepts any fantasy-land compatible applicative functor.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns the empty value of its argument's type.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Other types are supported if they define `<Type>.empty`, `<Type>.prototype.empty` or implement the FantasyLand Monoid spec.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to the `empty` method of the first argument, if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Checks if a list ends with the provided sublist.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Similarly, checks if a string ends with the provided substring.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Takes a function and two values in its domain and returns `true` if the values map to the same value in the codomain; `false` otherwise.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Reports whether two objects have the same value, in `R.equals` terms, for the specified property.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns `true` if its arguments are equivalent, `false` otherwise.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches symmetrically to the `equals` methods of both arguments, if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Creates a new object by recursively evolving a shallow copy of `object`, according to the `transformation` functions.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] A `transformation` function will not be invoked if its corresponding key does not exist in the evolved object.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Takes a predicate and a `Filterable`, and returns a new filterable of the same type containing the members of the given filterable which satisfy the given predicate.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Filterable objects include plain objects, Maps, or any object that has a filter method such as `Array`.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Dispatches to the `filter` method of the second argument, if present.
[src:ramda-functional/page-p01] Returns the first element of the list which matches the predicate, or `undefined` if no element matches.
