[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] 2. the function has no side effects (no mutation of non-local variables, mutable reference arguments or input/output streams).
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] I/O is inherently impure: input operations undermine referential transparency, and output operations create side effects.
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] The second point ensures that the only sequence usable as an argument must change with each I/O action; the first allows different calls to an I/O-performing function to return different results on account of the sequence arguments having changed.
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] The I/O monad is a programming idiom typically used to perform I/O in pure functional languages.
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] The outputs of a pure function can be cached in a look-up table.
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] Any result that is returned from a given function is cached, and the next time the function is called with the same input parameters, the cached result is returned instead of computing the function again.
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] Memoization can be performed by wrapping the function in another function (wrapper function).
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] By means of memoization, the computational effort involved in the computations of the function itself can be reduced, at the cost of the overhead for managing the cache and an increase of memory requirements.
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] Functions that have just the above property 2 – that is, have no side effects – allow for compiler optimization techniques such as common subexpression elimination and loop optimization similar to arithmetic operators.
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] A C++ example is the `length` method, returning the size of a string, which depends on the memory contents where the string points to, therefore lacking the above property 1.
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] can be optimized such that the value of `s.length()` is computed only once, before the loop.
[src:ramda-functional/pure-function] Since pure functions have identical return values for identical arguments, they are well suited to unit testing.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] A practical functional library for JavaScript programmers.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] There are already several excellent libraries with a functional flavor.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Typically, they are meant to be general-purpose toolkits, suitable for working in multiple paradigms.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] We wanted a library designed specifically for a functional programming style, one that makes it easy to create functional pipelines, one that never mutates user data.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] The last two points together make it very easy to build functions as sequences of simpler functions, each of which transforms the data and passes it along to the next.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Ramda is designed to support this style of coding.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Using Ramda should feel much like just using JavaScript.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] We're not introducing lambda expressions in strings, we're not borrowing consed lists, we're not porting over all of the Clojure functions.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Our basic data structures are plain JavaScript objects, and our usual collections are JavaScript arrays.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] We also keep other native features of JavaScript, such as functions as objects with properties.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Functional programming is in good part about immutable objects and side-effect free functions.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] While Ramda does not *enforce* this, it enables such style to be as frictionless as possible.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] We aim for an implementation both clean and elegant, but the API is king.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] We sacrifice a great deal of implementation elegance for even a slightly cleaner API.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Last but not least, Ramda strives for performance.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] A reliable and quick implementation wins over any notions of functional purity.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] These script tags add the variable `R` on the browser's global scope.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Or you can inject ramda into virtually any unsuspecting website using the bookmarklet.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] It is possible to build Ramda with a subset of the functionality to reduce its file size.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Ramda's build system supports this with command line flags.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] This requires having Node/io.js installed and ramda's dependencies installed (just use `npm install` before running partial build).
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Also available is our Cookbook of functions built from Ramda that you may find useful.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] It could as easily have been `eweda`, but then we would be forced to say *eweda lamb!*, and no one wants that.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] For non-English speakers, lambs are baby sheep, ewes are female sheep, and rams are male sheep.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] So perhaps ramda is a grown-up lambda... but probably not.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] You can use testem to test across different browsers (or even headlessly), with livereloading of tests.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Install testem (`npm install -g testem`) and run `testem`.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Open the link provided in your browser and you will see the results in your terminal.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] If you have *PhantomJS* installed, you can run `testem -l phantomjs` to run the tests completely headlessly.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Destructuring imports from ramda *does not necessarily prevent importing the entire library*.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Manually cherry picking methods is cumbersome, however.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Most bundlers like Webpack and Rollup offer tree-shaking as a way to drop unused Ramda code and reduce bundle size, but their performance varies, discussed here.
[src:ramda-functional/ramda-ramda] Webpack only - use `UglifyJS` plugin for treeshaking along with the `ModuleConcatenationPlugin`.
